        "content": "QUICK REFERENCE\nAvalora Referral Partner\nGatekeeper Script\nShort, calm responses for getting past the gatekeeper to the\ndecision-maker .\nGoal\nGet to the decision-maker or get the best way to send the short demo.\nDo not pitch the gatekeeper .\nDo not explain everything.\nDo not sound like a salesperson.\nUse a calm, slightly unsure tone, like you are asking for help.\n\nPRIMARY SCRIPT\nMain Gatekeeper Opener\n\"Hey, maybe you can help me out for a second.\nI'm trying to reach [Name] . This is Burhan with Avalora.\nIt's not a patient call or anything urgent. I'm reaching out because we're\nbuilding a small referral partner circle around Miami med spas and\naesthetic clinics, and I wanted to get a short demo in front of [Name]  to\nsee if it's relevant to their network.\nWould [Name]  be the right person for that?\"\nIf They Ask: \"What Is This Regarding?\"\n\"Of course.\nAvalora helps Miami med spas recover missed calls, after-hours\ninquiries, and booking requests before patients go cold.\nBut I'm not calling to sell [Name]  anything. It's more of a partner\nconversation \u2014 if they know clinics where this is useful, there's a simple\npartner thank-you when an introduced clinic becomes a paid client.\n\nThe first step is just getting the short demo in front of them.\"\nThen ask:\n\"Would it be best to transfer me, or is there a better email for that?\"\nIf They Ask: \"Is This a Sales Call?\"\n\"Not really in the normal sense.\nI'm not calling to sell [Name]  a service for their company .\nIt's more of a referral partner conversation. W e want to show a short\ndemo first, and if it feels useful for clinics in their network, we can talk\nabout introductions later .\"\nThen ask:\n\"Would [Name]  usually handle something like that?\"\n\nIf They Say: \"Send Information\"\n\"Sure, I can do that.\nWhat's the best email to send the short demo and context to?\nAnd should I address it directly to [Name] ?\"\nAfter they give email:\n\"Perfect. And just so I don't send it into the wrong place \u2014 is [Name]  the\nright person for partner conversations, or is there someone else who\nhandles relationships like this?\"\nIf They Say: \"[Name] Is Not Available\"\n\"No problem.\nWhat's the best way to get a short demo and note in front of them?\nI don't want to send a long pitch \u2014 it's just a quick partner demo for\nclinics in the aesthetic space.\"\nThen ask:\n\n\"Would email be best, or should I call back at a better time?\"\nIf They Ask: \"Do They Know You?\"\n\"Not yet.\nThat's why I'm being direct. I came across [Company]  because of their\nwork in the aesthetic space, and I thought Avalora may be relevant as a\npartner resource.\nI just wanted to get the demo in front of [Name]  first before asking for\nany type of conversation.\"\n\nIf They Push Back\n\"I understand.\nI don't want to waste anyone's time. The only reason I reached out is\nbecause Avalora is specifically focused on Miami med spas, missed-call\nrecovery , and booking support.\nIf it is not relevant, no problem.\nWho would be the best person to decide whether this is worth looking\nat?\"\nTRANSFER OPTIONS\nClean T ransfer Ask\nOption 1:\n\"Would you be able to connect me with [Name]  for a quick\nminute?\"\nOption 2:\n\"What's the cleanest way to get this in front of [Name] ?\"\nOption 3:\n\n\"Should I send the demo to you, or directly to [Name] ?\"\nREFERENCE\nTone Notes\nSound calm and helpful.\nUse \"maybe you can help me out\" at the start.\nDo not overexplain.\nDo not say \"commission.\"\nUse \"partner thank-you\" if compensation comes up.\nDo not ask the gatekeeper for referrals.\nOnly ask for access, email, or the right person.\n\n"
